83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
A-Engrossed
House Bill 4069
Ordered by the House February 12
Including House Amendments dated February 12
Introduced and printed pursuant to House Rule 12.00. Presession filed (at the request of House Interim Committee
on Behavioral Health)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: The Act requires a safety plan in certain mental health and SUD treatment settings.
(Flesch Readability Score: 65.7).
Requires a behavioral health employer to [develop and] implement a written safety policy or
plan for the physical safety of individuals working for the behavioral health employer.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to the safety of behavioral health workers; and prescribing an effective date.
3 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
4 SECTION 1. (1) As used in this section:
5 (a) “Behavioral health employer” means any of the following entities that contract with
6 the Oregon Health Authority for the provision of behavioral health services:
7 (A) A residential treatment facility, as defined in ORS 443.400;
8 (B) A residential treatment home, as defined in ORS 443.400;
9 (C) A secure residential treatment facility, as described in ORS 443.465;
10 (D) A secure residential treatment home, as described in ORS 443.465;
11 (E) A sobering facility, as defined in ORS 430.306;
12 (F) A detoxification center, as defined in ORS 430.306;
13 (G) A halfway house, as defined in ORS 430.306;
14 (H) A mobile crisis intervention team, as defined in ORS 430.626; or
15 (I) An emergency shelter.
16 (b) “Built environment” includes facilities, vehicles and other physical locations where
17 work is performed on an ongoing basis.
18 (c) “Lone worker” means an individual who directly provides or assists with the delivery
19 of behavioral health services and works in a situation or location without a colleague nearby
20 or without close or direct supervision.
21 (2) A behavioral health employer shall:
22 (a) Implement a written policy or plan for the physical safety of individuals working for
23 the behavioral health employer.
24 (b) Provide a copy of the safety policy or plan to new workers upon hire.
25 (3) A safety policy or plan required under this section must:
26 (a) Include a plan for addressing the physical safety of lone workers.
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 229

A-Eng. HB 4069
1 (b) Include a plan for the safety of the built environment, including:
2 (A) How workers may report structural security hazards; and
3 (B) The time frame within which the behavioral health employer must respond to a re-
4 port of a structural security hazard.
5 (c) Include information for workers about the safety training that the behavioral health
6 employer is required to provide under ORS 430.775, including the time frame within which
7 the employer must provide all required training for a new worker and how often the em-
8 ployer must provide renewal training for current workers.
9 (d) Be tailored to the behavioral health employer’s specific context.
10 (e) Be easily accessible to staff.
11 SECTION 2. The requirements under section 1 of this 2026 Act apply to behavioral health
12 employers as follows:
13 (1) For a behavioral health employer that does not have a contract with the authority in
14 effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act, the requirements apply on the date on which the
15 behavioral health employer first enters into a contract with the authority for the provision
16 of behavioral health services.
17 (2) For a behavioral health employer that has an existing contract with the authority in
18 effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act, the requirements apply on the effective date of
19 the first renewal, extension or amendment of that contract occurring after the contract’s
20 expiration.
21 SECTION 3. This 2026 Act takes effect on July 1, 2027.
